A huge opportunity missed by Nurul Hasan and Shakib Al Hasan cannot believe it. Nicely tossed up, on a length and outside off. Shreyas Iyer shimmies down the track and gets completely beaten in the flight. Nurul Hasan is a bit too excited to whip off the bails and ends up spilling it.
Flatter and shorter, angled into leg stump, Iyer keeps it out.
Quicker one on off stump, Pant keeps it out in front of point.
This is tossed up around leg stump, Pant lunges forward and keeps it out.
Flatter delivery on off stump, Pant blocks it out.

Quicker one on the pads, Rishabh Pant tickles it 'round the corner for a couple and that will be FIFTY for Pant as well. This has been just the counter-attacking inning that India were looking for but he still has a bit of work to do.
SIX! BANG! This is tossed up by Taijul outside off and turning in. Rishabh Pant just holds his shape and slog-sweeps it over the wide long on fence for a biggie.
Straight as an arrow! Tossed up around middle, Rishabh Pant advances and drills it right back into the stumps at the other end.
Tossed up on off stump, Iyer keeps it out.
Flighted delivery, around off and eased away toward extra cover.
Up and over! Tossed up outside off, Rishabh Pant comes down the track and miscues the lofted shot over covers for a single. The 50 partnership between these two is up in quick time.
Holds it back a touch and floats it around off, Shreyas Iyer caresses it through the cover region for a single.
Flatter delivery on leg stump, this is nudged away toward mid-wicket for a quick single.

FOUR! Runs are flowing at the moment and India are taking a big chunk out of Bangladesh's lead. This is shorter and turning down leg, Pant goes back and just tickles it fine. The ball goes into the fine leg fence.
Shakib Al Hasan comes into the attack now.
Just shortens the length a bit and bowls it on middle, Iyer goes back in his crease to keep it out.
This is angled into middle and leg, Iyer defends it off the front foot.
Floated up full and on middle, Rishabh Pant knocks it down to long on for a single.
Around middle, Pant strides forward to defend.
Flatter delivery around leg stump, Pant looks to work it off the back foot but misses and gets hit on the pads.
Taijul Islam comes back on and starts from around the wicket. This is fired in around the pads and Pant pads it away past leg slip.
Pitched up around middle, Pant pushes it gently to the right of mid on and scampers through for one.

FOUR! Poor bowling this from Khaled Ahmed, not bowling to his field. The mid-wicket is stationed now but Khaled bowls it short and around off, Pant waits for it and smartly just dabs it behind point for another boundary.
FOUR! Easy pickings! Full and on middle and leg, Rishabh Pant whips it across and gets it well in front of the square on the leg side for a boundary.
This is pitched up on off stump, Rishabh Pant defends it out toward mid off.
Full and on middle and leg, Pant blocks it back to the bowler.
A bit of swing but down the wrong line. Full and on the pads, swinging down the leg side, Nurul Hasan does well to dive to his right and get a glove on it.
Khaled Ahmed comes into the attack now.
Back of a length and around off, cut away hard and towards deep point for a single. India trail by exactly 100 runs now.
A touch fuller and angling in from around off, Pant punches it out toward extra cover.
Pitched up in that channel outside off and Pant lets it through to the keeper.
NO BALL! Around the top of off and angling in, Iyer hits it on the up toward extra cover and picks up a single. Taskin has overstepped and a no ball is called.

Slight halt! A tough chance as Mehidy Hasan puts down a catch and the ball has deflected onto his face but his face hit the turf hard and that is what has done the damage. Blood starts to come down his nose and the physio has rushed out to check him. Mehidy is taken off the field just as precaution and the play can now resume.

DROPPED! Mehidy Hasan almost pulls off a spectacular catch but might have just hurt himself here. Back of a length and outside off, Shreyas Iyer pushes at it with hard hands and gets a thick outside edge toward the gully region. Mehidy flies to his right and almost grabs it with his right hand. The ball pops out and as Mehidy tries to grab it on the second attempt, his forehead thuds into the turf and that could be really painful, hope he is fine.

FOUR! Extra bounce and Shreyas Iyer gets lucky there. Good length outside off, Iyer looks to punch but gets a bit taken aback. The ball goes off the outer half of the bat and uppishly behind point for a boundary.

Half an appeal from the bowler for lbw but the umpire remains unmoved. Good length, around the top of off and nipping back in off the deck. Shreyas Iyer gets squared up and gets an inside edge onto the pads.
Beaten! Lovely delivery this from Mehidy Hasan as it is drifted into off stump and then just turns away from the left-hander. Rishabh Pant looks to block off the front foot but is well beaten.
Tossed up around off, kept out by Pant.
Shorter and drifted into middle and leg, Rishabh Pant wristily whips it through mid-wicket for a couple of runs.

Overthrows and four of them, unlucky! Mehidy Hasan tosses it up around middle, Shreyas Iyer tucks it toward square leg and sets off for the single. Najmul Hossain Shanto from mid-wicket runs to his right and scores a direct hit at the batter's end. The ball though hits the stumps and trickles away into the fence. It is sent upstairs and the replays show that Pant was well home, so, 5 runs added to the total.
Floats it up now around off, Iyer lunges forward to block.

Right then, India still trail by 141 runs and have 7 wickets in hand. They do bat deep and the middle order is in form as well but on a turning pitch and Taijul Islam spitting fire, a lot will depend on the pair of Virat Kohli and Rishabh Pant. Do join us for another riveting session of Test cricket as both sides look to get ahead in the game. The post-Lunch session begins at 11.40 am IST (6.10 am GMT).

India will be pretty disappointed with the session on the whole but mostly with how their openers got out. Last evening, KL Rahul got a reprieve when he tried to step out and just pad the ball away but he made the same mistake one too many times and was the first to fall. Shubman Gill followed suit soon after as he tried to sweep against the turn and this put the visitors on the back foot. Cheteshwar Pujara and Virat Kohli then put on a decent stand but neither looked to be in complete control before eventually Pujara was dismissed via a sharp catch by Mominul Haque at short leg. Since then, Rishabh Pant has looked positive and Kohli has just about hung on. They will look to bat throughout the next session and take their side to safer shores.

Session summary - 28 overs, 67 runs and 3 wickets. A session that has well and truly belonged to Bangladesh and they will be much pleased with that bowling effort. They are still lagging behind a bit because they don't have many runs to play with. Taijul Islam was the pick of the bowlers as he dismissed the Indian top three and could have had more as well. Apart from Taijul though, Mehidy Hasan has attacked a bit but has bowled far too many loose deliveries for the batters to score runs. The other bowlers didn't bowl much this morning and they might have to step up in the next session if the hosts are to expose the Indian lower order.

We are ready for the start of Day 2! The umpires and the Bangladesh players are out in the middle and so are the overnight batters for India, KL Rahul and Shubman Gill. Khaled Ahmed will get proceedings underway with the ball here.

PITCH REPORT - Sanjay Manjrekar says that there is a lot of wear and tear on the pitch that too on Day 2. Adds that on one side outside the right-hander's off stump, there are three roughs created mostly by Jaydev Unadkat and the Bangladeshi spinners will have a good chance of making use of it.

For Bangladesh, Mominul Haque was the only batter who put on a good showing with the bat. Their others batters kept on getting out at the opposite end. They managed to score 227 runs and their bowling side did well at the start troubling the Indian skipper, but he was saved by the DRS. They will be hoping to bag some early wickets on Day 2. Can they do it? Or will the Indians dominate on the second day as well? We shall find out together.

The Indian openers KL Rahul and Shubman Gill got a steady start with just one hiccup when Rahul was given out on the field but the decision was reversed. They will be hoping to put up a solid opening stand and put up a good lead over the opponents. Their bowlers did well too, as Umesh Yadav and Ravichandran Ashwin bagged four wickets and Jaydev Unadkat took two.

Hello and a warm welcome to Day 2 of the 2nd Test match between Bangladesh and India. It is the visitors who have had the better sleep for the night and the hosts are busy making the plans for the morning. Bangladesh were bundled out for 227 runs on Day 1. India will be hoping to put up a solid opening stand and put up some pressure on the hosts.
... Day 2, Session 1 ...

Right then, Day 1 of the 2nd Test between Bangladesh and India comes to an end, and certainly, it is the visitors who have the early advantage. There's still a lot of time remaining for the hosts to come back into the contest but they will want to make early inroads on Day 2 which will begin on Friday at 9 am IST (3.30 am GMT). Do join us early though for the build-up. Till then, take care and goodbye!

Umesh Yadav is down for a quick chat. Yadav says that a few of the balls were taking it off while some of the deliveries were seaming. Adds that there is something here for the fast bowlers and they just need to bowl in the right area. Ends by saying that there is grass but it is dead and that might be the reason for the spongey bounce.

Bangladesh opted to bat first and skipper Shakib Al Hasan mentioned that if they got through the first hour or so, they would be able to score big and they did just that, managing not to lose a wicket in the first hour but that didn't matter. Almost everyone in the top 6 got off to a start but it was only the ex-skipper and the man who was making a comeback in this Test, Mominul Haque who was able to make valuable runs for his side. With the score 213/5, Mehidy Hasan started feeling uneasy and had to take some pills but the very next over he got out playing a poor shot and from there Bangladesh lost 5 wickets for only 14 runs, being bowled out for a meager score of 227 runs. Taskin Ahmed and Shakib Al Hasan came out to bowl with the former being a bit wayward but the skipper created enough doubt for the batters to get that breakthrough but it never came and with still 6 overs remaining in the day, the play was called off for badlight.

A slight halt in play. Oh, wait the umpires have come together and decided that the light is insufficient and that will be Stumps on Day 1 just like that. So, India remained unscathed going into Day 2 and will be mightily pleased as to how the first day has panned out. They were asked to field first by Shakib Al Hasan and after facing stiff resistance from the Bangladesh openers for about 15 overs, the visitors did make inroads and throughout the first two sessions, they were able to pick up a wicket just when a partnership was starting to look dangerous. Jaydev Unadkat was brilliant and Umesh Yadav along with Ravichandran Ashwin were simply sensational in the final session. KL Rahul and Shubman Gill did look a bit unsettled and there were a couple of half-chances induced as well but they will end the day with all 10 wickets intact.

Good length around the top of off, Shubman Gill keeps it out.
Nicely bowled! Quicker and flatter, attacking the off stump, KL Rahul just about gets a bat on it. A maiden for Shakib Al Hasan.
Quicker one, looking to spear it into leg stump but drifts down leg a bit, Rahul nudges it onto the leg side.
Flatter one at the stumps, Rahul is able to keep this one out.
Beaten again! Nicely flighted, full and around off stump, Rahul looks to push at it but the ball turns away and zips past the outside edge.

An absolute ripper of a delivery from Shakib Al Hasan and KL Rahul is beaten all ends up. Gives it a bit more air and drifts it onto the pads, Rahul looks to block but the ball grips and turns square, beating the outside edge.
Just holds it back a touch and bowls it on off stump, KL Rahul watchfully keeps it out.
FOUR! Lucky boundary! Back of a length and around off, Shubman Gill looks to cut close from the body but ends up chopping it past the stumps. The ball runs away into the fine leg fence.
NO BALL! Taskin hits the deck hard and bowls it at 138 clicks around off. Shubman Gill stays back and nudges it onto the off side. The bowler has overstepped and a no ball is called.
Length again but this is pushed a fair bit outside the off stump, Shubman Gill doesn't play at it.
Length ball, right on the money and solidly defended out of the front foot by Gill.
KL Rahul is off the mark! Shortish length, angled in from around off, Rahul plays it off the back foot towards cover and picks up a single.
Hits the length hard and bowls it around off, KL Rahul hops and keeps it down on the off side.
Good length, in that channel around off and angling in. KL Rahul makes a watchful leave as the ball goes a few inches above the off stump.
End of a probing first over by Shakib Al Hasan. Flatter one around off, Shubman Gill solidly punches it out toward cover.
This is fired in from around off and angling in, Gill looks to drive but gets another inside edge.
Flatter one around off, Shubman Gill looks to cut but gets an inside edge back onto the deck.
Around off, pushed out onto the off side.
Shubman Gill and India are underway! Floated, full and on middle, Gill clips it away well in front of the square on the leg side for a couple of runs.
Just short! Shakib Al Hasan almost gets rid of Shubman Gill right away. Tossed up, full and outside off, Gill goes for the drive but hits it uppishly toward point. Gets lucky there Gill.
Shakib Al Hasan to bowl from the other end.
A maiden to start off with! Length ball, around the fifth stump line and shaping away nicely. KL Rahul plays inside the line of the ball.
Fuller in length and around off, moving a bit in the air as well, Rahul pushes it out on the off side.
Taskin hits the deck hard and angles it in from around off. Rahul hops on the back foot and keeps it down toward cover.
A bit shorter and outside off, KL Rahul looks to punch it off the back foot but mistimes it badly.
Goes full and wide now, a hint of shape away as well. KL Rahul lets it through to the keeper.
Taskin Ahmed starts right on the money as he serves a length ball around the top of off. KL Rahul defends it solidly off the front foot.

We are back for the chase and there are still 23 overs remaining in the day! The umpires are out in the middle and so are the players of Bangladesh. KL Rahul and Shubman Gill are the openers for India. It will be the skipper, Shakib Al Hasan who will take the new ball. Let's play...
... FOURTH INNINGS ...

Right then, 145 needed for India to win the game and seal the series 2-0 and it should be a simple chase for them. The pitch has enough in it for the Bangladeshi bowlers to trouble the Indian top-order but one good stand and it can all be over. The hosts will look to take the game as deep as possible whilst India will be hoping that their top order doesn't falter. Join us fot the chase in a bit.

India were highly frustrated towards the end of the second session as Bangladesh found a way of scoring freely and that continued after the break. However, they knew that if they got one wicket, they could rip through the tail and that is exactly what happened. Axar Patel finished with 3 as Ravichandran Ashwin and Mohammed Siraj both got a couple of wickets each. They bundled out Bangladesh for 231 runs and now need a modest total to whitewash the hosts.

An unfortunate end to the innings for Bangladesh but they have something on the board to defend. After the Tea break, the hosts lost their remaining 3 wickets for 36 runs and have set India 145 runs to win. Litton Das and Taskin Ahmed came out with positive intent in the final session and were able to find the fence. They ran well too but Mohammed Siraj dismissed Litton Das with a gem of a delivery and that opened the floodgates for India. In general, the likes of Zakir Hasan and Litton Das were the only ones to play a good knock and cameos from Nurul Hasan and Taskin Ahmed took the lead close to 150 runs but it still seems a bit low.

OUT! RUN OUT! This was a blunder from the Bangladesh batters and they are bowled out for 231. Bowls it on off, Khaled Ahmed pushes it to short mid-wicket and sets off for a single. Shubman Gill grabs it quickly and throws it a bit high towards Axar Patel at the non striker's end. He is quick enough to whip the bails off. The replay shows that Khaled Ahmed was just behind the line and Bangladesh are bundled out for 231 runs. Bangladesh end with a lead of 144 runs.
Commentary.Howout: run out (Shubman Gill / Axar Patel)

Commentary.Commentary: Is that a run-out? Looked like a straightforward opportunity but the throw from Shubman Gill wasn't the best. Khaled Ahmed nudges it in front of short leg and Taskin Ahmed calls him for the single. Khaled seems to be struggling at the bowler's end as Axar Patel dislodges the bails and after checking the replays it is found that Khaled is just short. OUT is the decision on the big screen.
Fuller and on off, Khaled Ahmed lunges and blocks it away.
Bowls it on off, Taskin Ahmed knocks it but finds the man at mid off.
Another fuller one as this one is defended back towards the bowler.
Fuller and keeps it a tad low, Taskin Ahmed eases it to short covers.
Another fuller one as this is again defended towards the man at mid off.
Fuller and on off, Taskin Ahmed defends it to mid off.
Slightly shorter and on leg, Taskin Ahmed flicks it to deep mid-wicket for a brace. This is good running between the wickets.
Fuller and on off, Khaled Ahmed defends it solidly towards the man at covers.
Touch fuller and just outside off, Khaled Ahmed looks to play at it but misses.
On a length and on leg, Taskin Ahmed awkwardly lifts it towards square for a single. The ball carried a bit but landed safely.
FOUR! Smashed away. Slightly shorter and on off, Taskin Ahmed hangs back and smashes it over mid off for a boundary!
Fuller and on off, Taskin Ahmed taps it to the man at mid off.
Back of a length angling in, Taskin looks to go for a big heave but misses.
Turn and bounce here, Khaled gets an edge through to the third man, but decides not to take a single.
Fuller on the stumps, Khaled defends it back to the bowler.
FOUR! Fuller and down leg, Khaled Ahmed reads it well and gives it a slight tickle as the ball races away the fine leg fence for a boundary!
Bowls it down leg, Ahmed looks to defend it but misses and gets his pads. A stifled appeal turned down.
Fuller and outside off, Ahmed looks to play at it but misses.
Khaled Ahmed is the last man in for Bangladesh.

OUT! LBW! This one is a touch fuller and angling in from middle and leg, Taijul Islam looks to block it but misses and gets a rap on his pads. A loud appeal and the finger goes up. Taijul Islam decides to go upstairs immediately. Fair delivery and Ultra Edge shows no spike. Ball Tracking shows three reds as the ball is just clipping leg stump and Bangladesh go nine down in a jiffy!
Commentary.Howout: lbw b Ravichandran Ashwin

Commentary.Commentary: Ravichandran Ashwin (20-2-60-1) is back on.
Touch fuller and on off, Ahmed defends it solidly towards covers.
Fuller and on leg, Taijul clips it to backward square leg for a single.
Another one outside off shaping it away, Taijul looks to play at it but misses again!
Fuller and just outside off, Taijul looks to defend it but misses. Close!
On a length and outside off, Taijul gets in two minds but leaves it alone in the end.
Taijul Islam is the new man in.

OUT! TIMBER! Mohammed Siraj, you beauty! Keeps on making use of that scrambled seam and bowls it on a good length around off. This one jags back in sharply off the deck. Litton Das looks to defend it but gets caught on the crease and is beaten on the inside edge as the ball rattles into the stumps. An excellent innings from Litton Das comes to an end as he walks back into the hut for 73! Bangladesh lead by 132 runs.
Commentary.Howout: b Mohammed Siraj

Commentary.Commentary: Fuller and on off, Das guides it to covers for a single.
This one lands on off, Das lunges and defends it away.
Fuller one and on off, it keeps a tad low. Ahmed plays it with soft hands towards covers for a single.
KL Rahul is currently off the ground for a reason unknown at the moment. Abhimanyu Easwaran is the substitute fielder and Cheteshwar Pujara is the acting captain in Rahul's absence.
Bowls it on off this time, Das steers it to point for a single.
Another one on middle, Das defends it to the gully region.
Flatter and on middle as this is defended back towards the bowler.
Short of a length and outside off, Taskin Ahmed throws his hands at it and slashes it wide of the man at third man for a couple of runs.

Litton Das knew straightaway that it was pitching outside leg. A length ball around leg and angling across. Taskin Ahmed looks to flick but falls over a bit and gets pinged in front of the stumps. There is a huge appeal for lbw from Mohammed Siraj, pleading for it and the finger does go up. Taskin Ahmed has immediately reviewed it and if the ball is pitching outside leg, he might be saved. Nothing on UltraEdge and Ball Tracking does show that it is pitching well outside the line of leg stump and the decision is reversed.
Goes a bit wider of the crease and angles it in on a hard length. Litton Das stays back and dabs it past point for a single.
Fuller, at 141 clicks and angled into middle. Litton Das looks to loft it over mid on but mistimes it badly.
Hits a good length and angles it in from around off. The scrambled seam makes the ball bounce a bit extra and Litton Das manages to keep it down in front of the man at gully.
Bowls it full and wide, Litton Das looks to drive it straight but mistimes it back to the bowler who threatens to throw the ball back onto the stumps.
This is angled into the stumps, Taskin works it toward short mid-wicket.
Looks to fire it in from around off, Taskin prods forward to defend.
Flighted delivery around off, blocked out.
A tad shorter and turning it into the pads, Taskin flicks it towards mid-wicket.
This is tossed up around off stump, Taskin Ahmed defends it off the front foot.
This is fired in around off stump, Litton Das presses forward and nudges it onto the leg side for a single.
A bumper now, over leg stump and bowled at a good pace as well. Taskin Ahmed ducks under it well though.
Full and down the leg side, Ahmed looks to flick but misses.
On a hard length, angling into middle and leg, Das manages to play it on the leg side and pick up a single.
Excellent running! Good length around the pads, Taskin Ahmed dabs it down in front of mid-wicket and sets off for the quick single.
Goes fuller now at 140 clicks and tightens the line around off stump. Taskin looks to play at it but the ball keeps low and beats the outside edge.

FOUR! Back of a length, at 143 clicks and angling across the off stump. Taskin Ahmed stands tall and guides it off the outer half of the bat past the slip cordon and into the fence. The 50-run stand is up between these two.

A slight mix-up in the middle but no harm is done. Quicker and shorter around off, this is tapped away off the back foot to the right of the man at point. Taskin Ahmed looks to get to the striker's end but is sent back halfway down the track by Litton Das and rightly so.
FOUR! Poor delivery from Axar Patel, a fraction shorter and outside off, Litton Das cuts it past the fielder at backward point and picks up another boundary.
Nagging length outside off and turning away. Litton Das gets caught on the crease and tentatively looks to cut but is beaten past the outside edge.
Quicker one, sliding through on off stump. Litton Das defends it off the back foot.
Short again and down the leg side, Taskin Ahmed gets down on one knee and pulls it toward fine leg for a run.
Shorter delivery on middle, this is worked away to deep mid-wicket for an easy single.
Axar Patel to bowl from the other end.
Banged in short and outside off, Taskin Ahmed looks to take it on but is beaten all ends up.
Beaten! A touch fuller and slanted just across the off stump. Taskin Ahmed looks to play at it but the ball zips past the outside edge.
A length ball, angling across from leg stump, Taskin Ahmed nudges it toward short mid-wicket.
Litton Das looks to charge down the track but Siraj pulls the length back a bit. Das ends up slicing it safely over covers for a single. The 200 is now up for Bangladesh.
FOUR! Litton Das isn't going to back down here. Pitched up outside off, Das lofts it up and over the point region for a boundary.

Starts off with a good-length delivery around off. This one jags back in a long way and Litton Das gets squared up while looking to flick. The ball hits him high on the pads and there's half an appeal for lbw but it is turned down.

We are back for the final session of Day 3. The Indian players are seen out in a huddle near the ropes. Litton Das and Taskin Ahmed will resume their innings. Mohammed Siraj comes to bowl. Here we goo.
... DAY 3, SESSION 3 ...

Right then, just the last three wickets to go and India will be hoping to get those in the next session and bundle their opponents. Bangladesh will hope to bat the entire session and take the play to the next day. Will the Indians continue to dominate with the ball? Or will Bangladesh put up a gritty stand and keep on batting till the session ends? We will find out shortly. Do join us at 2.00 pm IST (8.30 am GMT) post tea break.

Bangladesh has struggled and they have struggled a lot with the bat throughout the game. They will need something special to claw their way up in the game. They were saved a couple of times and still are seven down. Litton Das has reached his half-century and he will be the one who will need to keep the scoreboard ticking for his team. Nonetheless, he would need good support from the tailenders and try not to lose any further wickets. They have a lead of 108 runs now and will hope to add more to it as any lead of around 200 could be very handy on this pitch.

A good display of bowling once again from the Indians as they took 3 wickets in this session. Umesh Yadav started off by getting the dangerous Zakir Hasan and Mehidy Hasan soon followed the suit. Axar then got rid of Nurul Hasan then. He was the pick of the bowlers in this session as he took 2 wickets and almost got rid of the dangerous Litton Das who was saved by the review. There was a phase in the middle when Nurul Hasan and Litton Das ran a havoc over the India bowlers and stitched a quickfire 46-run partnership in 48 deliveries but it slowed down a bit once Nurul Hasan was dismissed.
Drifted onto the pads, flicked away through mid-wicket for one. That will be TEA on Day 3!

Slightly shorter and down leg, Taskin Ahmed looks to pull off the back foot but mistimes it past the man at leg slip for a single. The ball seems to have comes off the thigh pad and is signalled as leg byes.
Shorter and around off, this is punched away off the back foot toward cover for a single.
Good running. Slower and shorter around off, Taskin Ahmed nudges it toward backward point and scampers through for one.
On the pads and this is swept away fine toward deep backward square leg for a couple of runs. This has been a good fightback thus far from Bangladesh.
FOUR! Broomed away and the lead is now worth 102 runs! Tossed up on middle and leg, Taskin Ahmed slog-sweeps it between the man at deep mid-wicket and deep square leg for a boundary.

Flatter delivery around off, Litton Das goes on the back foot and plays it late toward third man. The man from first slip chases it down and the batters get a couple of runs. The lead is now inching closer to 100 runs.
FOUR! Up and over! Another one that's tossed up, Litton Das shimmies down the track and lofts it over mid on for a boundary.
Tosses it up now, full and around off, Taskin Ahmed mistimes the heave through mid on and picks up a single.
Just short! Flighted delivery around middle, Taskin Ahmed looks to block off the front foot but gets a faint inside edge that falls in front of the man at leg slip.
A tad shorter and down leg, this is pulled away toward fine leg for a couple of runs.

DROPPED! That will be FIFTY for Litton Das and this has been a very important knock for his side. Ravichandran Ashwin bowls a lovely delivery, drifting into off and turning away sharply off the deck. Das gets squared up and the outside edge is found. Virat Kohli at first slip springs to his right but fails to grab it with his right hand. The ball goes towards third man and a single is taken.
Flighted delivery, drifted on the pads and Taskin Ahmed gets an inside edge that goes wide of the fielder stationed at leg slip.
Comes from over the wicket now and bowls it a bit shorter around the pads, Taskin Ahmed fails to work it away.
Shorter and on the pads, this is worked off the back foot through mid-wicket for a single.
Around off, kept out by Litton Das.

What a review! Litton Das survives and there's a huge cheer from the crowd. Axar Patel fires this one in on the pads. Das looks to work it leg side but the ball skids on and thuds into the pads. There is a huge appeal and Litton Das has been adjudged lbw. Das does review it but this could be a huge moment in the game. Nothing on UltraEdge but Ball Tracking shows that the ball is going on with the arm and missing leg stump.
Flatter and quicker and around off, this is chopped off the back foot and in front of point.
Looks for the carrom ball but spills it down leg for the keeper to collect.
Floated up full and on off stump, Litton Das sweeps it toward deep backward square leg for a single.
Around middle, Litton Das watchfully blocks it out.
Tossed up on middle and leg, flicked away toward mid-wicket.

Three runs and it will be leg byes as well. On a length and drifting down leg, Taskin Ahmed looks to work it fine but misses. The ball goes off the pads and trickles down to fine leg before it is cut off.
Fuller and on off, Das flicks it to square leg for a single.
This one lands on off, Ahmed defends it with soft hands towards mid on.
Fuller one again, Ahmed taps it to short covers and calls for one but is sent back.
FOUR! Fuller and on off, Ahmed gets on his knee and slog sweeps it over mid-wicket for a boundary!
Fuller and on off, Das opens the face of the bat and plays it uppishly towards covers for one.
Bowls it on middle as this is defended back towards the bowler.
Fuller one and on leg, Das flicks it to deep backward square leg for a brace. Good running!
Fuller one and on leg, Das works it to mid-wicket for one.
Slightly shorter and on off, Das defends it back towards the bowler.
Bowls it on leg, Ahmed works it to mid-wicket for one.
Tosses it on off, Litton Das knocks it to mid on for one.
Bowls it fuller again, Litton Das flicks it to the man at mid-wicket.
Fuller and on off, Litton Das lunges and defends it away.
Another one on middle, turning it away, Taskin Ahmed looks to defend it but gets a rap on his pads. A loud appeal but the finger stays down and India is out of reviews. They are getting closer!
Fuller and on off, Taskin Ahmed defends it with soft hands towards mid off.
Quicker and outside off, Taskin Ahmed looks to play at it but misses.
Taskin Ahmed is the new man in.

OUT! STUMPED! This is slightly shorter and on off turning it away, Nurul Hasan shimmies down the wicket to loft it but misses it completely. Rishabh Pant pouches it and whips off the bails in no time. Bangladesh lost their seventh and they are in huge trouble now! The lead currently stands at 72 runs.
Commentary.Howout: st Rishabh Pant b Axar Patel

Commentary.Commentary: Fuller and on off, Hasan plays it towards the man at mid off. It carries for a while but lands safely.
Fuller and on middle, Das nudges it to mid-wicket for a single.
This is on off as Hasan defends it to the cover region.

Fuller and on off, Hasan looks to defend it but gets gets inbetween the bat and pads. Ashwin thinks it was pad first and appeals but the umpire is unmoved. India are also out of reviews so the onfield decision stands!
Slightly shorter and on leg, Das flicks it to mid-wicket for one.
Another one on off, Das taps it to the man at covers.
Tosses it on off, Das defends it to the point region.
Slightly shorter and on off, Das eases it to short mid-wicket. They wanted a single but decided not to take it.

Is that a fair catch? Virat Kohli isn't sure but seems to have got his man. The umpires come together and go upstairs. The soft signal is Not Out. This is tossed up around off stump and there's some sharp turn on offer as well. Nurul Hasan looks to press forward but gets an outside edge toward first slip. The replays show that the ball just bounced before going into Kohli's hands. Nurul is a relieved man.
At the stumps and blocked away.
Flatter one on middle, nudged away onto the leg side.

FOUR! It seems to be a dropped catch but maybe, there wasn't any bat involved. Tossed up on a length and Axar Patel extracts sharp turn and bounce yet again. Nurul Hasan looks to block off the front foot but the ball gets a feather off the outside edge and flicks the keeper's gloves before going past Virat Kohli at first slip and into the fence.
Pre-meditated from Nurul Hasan, looks to shuffle across and scoop but misses the shorter ball over the stumps.
On a length and around off, a bit of turn and bounce on offer as well. Nurul Hasan manages to defend it out.
Slightly shorter and on off, Litton Das punches it to point for a brace.
Short and wide outside off, Nurul Hasan cuts it to point for one.
Leg bye! This is shorter and down leg, Litton Das looks to flick off the back foot but gets it off his pads toward short fine leg. They get a leg bye.
Slightly shorter and on off, Hasan steers it to point for one again.
Bowls it on the leg side, Das works it to square leg for one.
Tossed up just outside off, Hasan guides it to backward point for a single.
This one almost goes through! Quicker one on a nagging length and on off stump. Litton Das goes on the back foot instead of coming forward but just about manages to get an inside edge on it.
Nagging length around off, Litton Das goes on the back foot and ease it toward cover.
Flatter delivery around off, Das taps it towards point.

FOUR! Bangladesh are on a roll here and the Indian spinners for the first time in this innings are under a bit of pressure. Tossed up around off, Litton Das gets down on one knee and brooms it in front of the square on the leg side for another boundary.
This is sliding into leg stump, Litton Das blocks it out.
FOUR! Litton Das gets into the act now. Tossed up on off stump, Das gets a big stride forward and sweeps it firmly into the mid-wicket fence.
Two more and the lead goes past 50 now! Short again and around off, this is chopped away and past the cover fielder for a couple of runs. This is good counter-attacking batting from Nurul Hasan.
Drops it short now and outside off, Nurul Hasan goes deep in his crease to cut it in front of the man at deep point for a couple of runs.
Quicker one, around middle, Nurul Hasan tentatively keeps it out.
Gives it a lot more air and drifts it onto leg stump, Nurul Hasan defends it out.
Pushes this one through a bit quicker and around off, Nurul Hasan edges it down with soft hands toward third man and races back for the second. Good running.
SIX! WOW! Ravichandran Ashwin comes back into the attack and starts with a tossed-up delivery on middle. Nurul Hasan dances down the track and whacks it over the long on fence for a biggie.
Flighted delivery around off, Litton Das lunges forward and makes the block.
Prodigious turn that time. Slows it up a touch and floats it around off, Litton Das looks to block off the front foot but the ball turns away square and goes a long way past the outside edge.
Bowls it on a length and drifts it onto middle, Litton Das presents a dead bat at it.
Sliding onto the pads, this is worked away 'round the corner for one.
Quicker one, on a length and angling in from around off. Axar Patel gets a bit of extra bounce but Nurul Hasan manages to keep it down in front of short leg.
Nagging length, close to the off pole and staying low. Nurul Hasan manages to keep it out.

Nicely played! Back of a length and outside off, Nurul Hasan punches it off the back foot in between point and cover. The two fielders chase it down and manage to stop the boundary. Enough time for the batters to take three there.

That could have gone anywhere. A bumper now, angled into the helmet of the batter. Nurul Hasan tries to get inside the line and take it on but mistimes it over the square leg region. The batters come back for two.
Fullish length, angling into the pads, Nurul Hasan manages to keep it out.
FOUR! A tad shorter and outside off, Nurul Hasan accepts the width and slaps it away in front of cover-point for a boundary.
Length ball angling in from middle and Das tucks it away past square leg for a single.
Yadav gets in the yorker now around off stump, Litton Das digs it out towards cover-point.
Drops it a bit short and bowls it on the pads, Nurul Hasan works it through mid-wicket for a couple of runs.
JAFFA! Fuller and around off, just slows it up a touch. Nurul Hasan looks to block but the ball turns away sharply just going past the outside edge.
This is fired in around the off pole and Nurul Hasan manages to keep it out.

Drinks! A great start to the second session as well for the visitors and the hosts lose two more in the first hour of the second session. Litton Das is still out there and he will be looking to build a gritty stand with any of the tailenders now! India will look to bundle their opponents as soon as they can. Nurul Hasan walks in next.

OUT! LBW! Mehidy Hasan departs and Bangladesh are now six down with a narrow lead of 26 runs. Axar Patel angles it in on a length and from a bit wider of the crease as well. This one pitches around the off stump and Mehidy looks to sweep with the angle as there is no one patrolling the square boundary on the leg side. Mehidy misses and gets pinged in front. The Indian players appeal and the finger goes up. Mehidy has a long chat with his partner before he accepts his fate and starts walking. Bangladesh in troubled waters now.
Commentary.Howout: lbw b Axar Patel

Commentary.Commentary: Angles this one in on middle and bowls it full, Mehidy Hasan blocks it out.
A bit shorter and on the pads, Litton Das goes back in his crease and pushes it out in front of mid-wicket for a run.
This is banged in short and outside off, Das dabs it down toward backward point and gets across for a single.
Full and around off, driven straight to the man at extra cover.
Back of a length around the fifth stump line, Litton Das defends it off the back foot.
On a hard length and around off, tapped away toward cover.
Just a touch fuller and angled into middle and off, the ball keeps a bit low and Das blocks it out.
Around the top of off, Litton Das blocks it from inside his crease.
Pushed through a bit and angling into the stumps, Mehidy Hasan blocks it out.
Nicely tossed up outside off, Litton Das looks to thrash it over extra cover but mistimes it toward sweeper cover for one.

DROPPED AND FOUR! Virat Kohli anticipates early and ends up going the wrong way. Axar Patel holds it back a touch and bowls it around off stump. Litton Das looks to drive with the turn but gets an outside edge. Kohli moves to his right but the ball goes to his left and he is unable to adjust in time. The ball hits the hand and trickles away into the third man fence.
Drifted onto middle, Das keeps it out.

FOUR! Streaky but a bit intentional as well. Tosses it up wide of the off stump, Litton Das presses forward and looks to open the face of the bat and guide it square of the wicket. The ball goes off the outside edge and flies past the diving fielder at first slip into the third man fence.
Floats it up on off stump, Litton Das pushes it toward cover.
Uppish but safe! Goes full now and attacks the pads, Mehidy Hasan looks to flick but ends up chipping it wide of the man at silly mid on.
Well bowled! Umesh Yadav goes a bit wider of the crease and angles it in on a length and into the off pole. The ball keeps a shade low but Mehidy Hasan manages to fend it away.
Mehidy Hasan walks in.

OUT! TAKEN! Not the best of deliveries from Umesh Yadav but he has got the big fish. This is short and wide, there to be hit. Zakir Hasan goes after it and slaps it away over backward point. Bangladesh have just 6 more wickets to play with and need an inspiring performance from someone here because the Indian bowlers will come at them hard. Will India tighten their grip on this match and wrap it up on Day 3? Or will the hosts pull off something spectacular? Join us for the post-Lunch session at 11.40 am IST (6.10 am GMT) for all the action.

India will be very content with that bowling display but will feel that they could have got a couple of more wickets. The surface has a lot in it for the spinners and it is all about being patient. Ravichandran Ashwin, Mohammed Siraj and Jaydev Unadkat all picked up a wicket each as they kept the hosts on their toes. This seemed to be enough going into the break but Axar Patel was introduced late in the session and he bowled a spell to Mushfiqur Rahim before eventually dismissing him. With just 6 more wickets to get and still leading by 16 runs, India will want to bundle out the opposition in the next session itself.

Bangladesh had a poor start to Day 3 as just in the second over of the day Najmul Hossain Shanto was dismissed and a few overs later, the star of the first innings, Mominul Haque also got out. Zakir Hasan and Shakib Al Hasan did look like stitching together a gritty stand but the skipper got out cheaply just like he did in the first innings. This had left the hosts reeling but with Zakir still out there alongside their most prolific Test batter Mushfiqur Rahim the hosts looked to steady the ship but it wasn't meant to be as Mushfiqur also got out late in the session, leaving the hosts in a spot of real bother.

A session that was filled with events and at the end of it, India will be the happier of the two sides as they have the hosts on the ropes at the moment. Bangladesh would want to better their batting effort in the next session and bat throughout but it won't be easy given what we have seen so far.

Rishabh Pant is in for a quick chat. He says that it was just a matter of time before he could capitalize and they both (Pant and Iyer) got their team out of trouble. Adds that unfortunately, he could not get to his century. Ends by saying that the pitch is a bit slower and they could have batted a bit better but they are in a good position having the lead.

Bangladesh were good with the ball as Taijul Islam and their skipper Shakib Al Hasan picked up 4 wickets each. Mehidy Hasan took one and Taskin Ahmed got rid of the dangerous Virat Kohli. Their openers then started off slow and defended the 6 overs they had to play towards the end of Day 2. They still trail by 80 runs but if they have a good opening stand, things can get even for them. Can they do it? Or will India bag some early wickets and put the hosts under pressure? We shall find out together.

India only needed more than 227 runs to surpass Bangladesh and put pressure on them, but the visitors had a shaky start and lost both of the openers in the first hour. They went down to three wickets in the first session and lost Virat Kohli at the very start of the second session. Rishabh Pant and Shreyas Iyer put up a gritty stand after that and scored 93 and 87 respectively. Once the two of them got out, India kept on losing wickets in a jiffy. They were finally bundled out for 314 having a lead of 87 runs. And, having bowled six overs late on Day 2 they haven't have made much impact with the new ball yet.

Hello and a warm welcome to Day 3 of the 2nd Test match between Bangladesh and India from Mirpur. The first day saw the visitors in the driver's seat as they bowled out the hosts at 227. The hosts clawed their way back on the second day and bundled out the visitors for 314, conceding a lead of under 100 runs. Both days saw a fall of ten wickets and it will be interesting to see which side will dominate the moving day.
... DAY 3, SESSION 1...

Right then, just like Day 1, 10 wickets fell on Day 2 as well and the contest is heating up nicely. With the pitch getting even more useful for the slower bowlers, India will hope that they are able to use a decent enough first-innings lead to their advantage. Bangladesh would want to occupy the crease for as long as possible as any sort of total they set could be difficult to chase down on Days 4 and 5 on this pitch. Day 3 is known as the moving day and it seems that we will get to see one team clearly taking the lead on this day. Action will begin on Saturday at 9 am IST (3.30 am GMT) but you can join us for the build-up a lot earlier. Cheers!

Shreyas Iyer is in for a quick chat. He says that they didn't have a good start and he likes to have challenges. Adds that he has been in such situations before and the pitch has everything for the spinners as the ball turns and bounces. Ends by saying that they need to execute their plans and come back stronger on Day 3..

India ended day 1 on a high and even though they don't finish Day 2 in the same manner, they will still feel that they are in control of this match. They lead by 80 runs but would have liked to pick up a wicket or two before the day ended. The top order seemed fragile and even though Virat Kohli stayed on the crease for long, he couldn't manage to convert his start. Then came the big 159-run stand between Rishabh Pant and Shreyas Iyer that put the visitors in the driving seat but a plethora of wickets fell in the final session and India failed to stretch their lead beyond 100 runs. With just 6 overs bowled by their bowlers late in the day, not many chances were created and they will now look to make early inroads on Day 3.

Bangladesh were on the ropes when India went into the Tea break with the score being 226/4 but skipper Shakib Al Hasan took matters into his own hands and about after a bit of a tussle, the breakthrough came. Pant was dismissed in the nervous 90s and that opened the floodgates for the hosts. Shakib and co were able to pounce on the opportunity and managed to bowl India out half an hour or so before the day ended. With an initial deficit of 87 runs, the Bangladeshi openers have done well to just negotiate the new ball and end the day unscathed.

Yet another eventful day of Test cricket comes to an end and heading into Day 3, it is India who have the edge over the hosts but all is not lost for Bangladesh here. They trail by runs 80 but have all 10 wickets in the bag and will be aware of the fact that one good stand at the top and the difference could be wiped out in no time.

KL Rahul collects the series-win trophy and the victorious Indian team poses for a team photo as well. That is it then from this game and from India's tour of Bangladesh as well. The hosts won the ODI series 2-1 and it is the visitors who have swept away the Test series 2-0 and kept their 2nd place in the World Test Championship Points table. Both teams are done for the year 2022 and India will now welcome Sri Lanka for a T20I and ODI series that will start on January 3, 2023. As for Bangladesh, they have a bit of a break before they return to international action. Hope you enjoyed our coverage and wish you and your family a Merry Christmas and a Happy New Year in advance. Until next time, take care and goodbye!

The Indian captain, KL Rahul says that when you play so much cricket together it is about trusting the guys in the middle. Adds that there is always a belief that someone will put their hand up and get the job done for the team. Shares that it is human nature to be nervous in situations like these. Feels that Ravichandran Ashwin and Shreyas Iyer showed a lot of composure on a tough wicket and played it with ease to get India the victory. Shares that they knew it was going to be difficult and they would need to grind on this wicket and work hard for runs. Feels that new ball does a lot more and it is about who plays the new ball well. Also says that it is about cashing in ocne the ball gets old. Says that will learn from this experience and get better as individuals. Feels that the depth in the fast bowling department has been good over the last 6-7 years and it showed in this Test with Mohammed Siraj, Umesh Yadav and Jaydev Unadkat delivering for the side. Ends by saying that Ashwin and Axar Patel too chipped in to bundle Bangladesh out.

Cheteshwar Pujara is the PLAYER OF THE SERIES for his sensational batting in both innings of the first Test match. He says that it was a very competitive series. Shares that he had put in a lot of hard work by working on his game and playing first-class games. Adds that that is important to be in touch by playing first-class games. Feels that is important to win each and every Test considering the World Test Championship. Also says that is important to be on top of the game. Ends by saying that ups and downs are a part of a cricketer's journey and it is all about being mentally strong and bouncing back.

Ravichandran Ashwin is the PLAYER OF THE MATCH for his brilliant contribution with both bat and the ball. Ashwin says that the game was on the line and there wasn't much batting left so is happy to have done the job. Adds that Bangladesh played well and put them under pressure but applauds Shreyas Iyer for the way he played and they got over the line. Mentions that they would have liked to play more shots but the bowling was good and they needed to trust their defense a bit more as well. Adds that the pitch was good, it was a bit slow but the ball got softer after 30 or so overs and the same ball could have been played off the front foot as well as the back foot. Ends by saying that barring the first innings in Chattogram, Bangladesh played really well and it was a well-contested series.

Shakib Al Hasan, the skipper of Bangladesh, says that everyone contributed in this game. Adds that at Mirpur they always have a chance. Feels that they put on a good show and it was what the crowd wanted with both sides playing very good Test cricket. Credits Shreyas Iyer and Ravichandran Ashwin with the way they batted and feels that they absorbed pressure well. Shares that it is his job to contribute with both bat and ball and it was unfortunate that he could not bowl in the first Test. Reckons that they needed one more wicket to get into the tail of India. Shares that he is happy with the way they fought. Ends by saying that they can only improve from hereon.
The presentation ceremony...

Earlier in the game, Shakib Al Hasan won the toss and opted to bat first on a track that had loads of grass on it but it wasn't live grass. The Bangladeshi batters all got off to starts in the first innings but no one apart from Mominul Haque could convert those starts. For India, Umesh Yadav and Ravichandran Ashwin starred with the ball as both of them picked up four wickets each. The Indian top-order faltered and it was a big 150-plus stand between Shreyas Iyer and Rishabh Pant that gave India a sizeable first-innings lead. Shakib Al Hasan and Taijul Islam also got four wickets each. The hosts were in a lot of trouble in their second innings but a fighting half-century from Zakir Hasan and a couple of quickfire knocks from Litton Das and Nurul Hasan gave them a final lead of 144 runs. The target wasn't a big one but it was a tricky wicket and the hosts gave it their all but the experience of Ravichandran Ashwin shone through as he took India to victory.

'The one that got away' - this is what Bangladesh will feel about this game. They were under the caush throughout the first couple of days but came roaring back on Day 3 with some scintillating batting and then magical bowling as well. Their spinners had their tail up coming into Day 4 and neither Shakib Al Hasan nor Mehidy Hasan disappoint. Mehidy went on to pick up a famous five-for but once Iyer and Ashwin started to consolidate, the Bangladeshi spinners lost their line and lengths. With not many runs to play with, too many boundary balls were bowled and India didn't let them off the hook. In the end, Bangladesh had no answer to the depth in India's batting and their batters just didn't put up enough runs on the board for them to get the win.

It was a fairly even contest coming into Day 4 but Bangladesh did have the upper hand and they become the favorites to win the game when Mehidy Hasan and Shakib Al Hasan picked up three quick wickets early in the day. India had their backs against the wall but have managed to turn misery into joy. Jaydev Unadkat was the first to fall on Day 4 and then Axar Patel and Rishabh Pant both fell in quick succession. With still 71 needed to win and the Bangladeshi spinners on top of proceedings, Shreyas Iyer and Ravichandran Ashwin stitched together an unbeaten partnership with the latter going on to end things with a flurry of boundaries toward the end. A remarkable win for the visitors and they will return home jubilant.

What a game! What a ripper of a contest we have witnessed in Mirpur! It is a Christmas Miracle as India have recovered from being 74 for 7 down to going on to win the game. Shreyas Iyer and Ravichandran Ashwin, take a bow. But spare a thought for Bangladesh and especially Mehidy Hasan who gave it his all and even picked up a five-wicket haul only to end up on the losing side. India seal the series 2-0 and keep their unbeaten record against Bangladesh is Test matches intact.

OUT! LBW! Shakib Al Hasan strikes in his first over of the day! Shakib Al Hasan bowls this one quicker and touch fuller on off, Jaydev Unadkat goes back to punch this one and pays the price as he gets caught plumb in front of the stumps. After a word with Axar Patel, he decides to review. The UltraEdge shows no bat and it is three reds on BallTracking. Jaydev Unadkat has to depart and India lose their review.
Commentary.Howout: lbw b Shakib Al Hasan

Commentary.Commentary: Leg bye! On a length around leg and turning in, Axar Patel looks to fend this one but the ball comes off his pads towards short fine leg for a single.
Short and on middle by Shakib Al Hasan, Jaydev Unadkat goes back and punches it to cover for a single.
Flighted, fuller around off, Jaydev Unadkat gets forward and defends it to cover.
Shakib Al Hasan to operate from the other end.
Length delivery on middle, Axar Patel pushes this one back to the bowler.
On a length around middle, Jaydev Unadkat sweeps this one down towards square leg for a single.
SIX! BANG! Full and on off by Mehidy Hasan, Jaydev Unadkat gets down on one knee and slog sweeps this one towards deep mid-wicket. Clears the fence with ease and collects a maximum.

Mehidy Hasan fires this one quicker, full and on middle, Jaydev Unadkat looks to defend this one and gets rapped on the pads. A loud appeal but the umpire shakes his head. Shakib Al Hasan decides to send it upstairs. The UltraEdge shows that it was pad first but on BallTracking it is umpire's call as it was clipping the leg stump and so the onfield decision stands.
Full on middle by Mehidy Hasan, Jaydev Unadkat rolls his wrist and executes the sweep to perfection. A fumble at short fine leg allows the batters to run two there.
Mehidy Hasan starts with a length delivery at the pads, Jaydev Unadkat gets forward to defend, the ball comes off his gloves and falls just short of Litton Das at first slip.

We are all set for the play to commence on Day 4! The umpires walk out to the middle as the Bangladeshi players can be seen raring to go around the boundary ropes. The overnight batters for India, Jaydev Unadkat and Axar Patel stride out to the middle as well and it will be the former who will face the first delivery of the day. Mehidy Hasan, the star with the ball on Day 3 will start proceedings on Day 4. Let's play...

India's top-order woes continued in the big games as all went out for cheap scores and neither of them for once looked settled on the crease. Axar Patel has been their best batter so far but with the likes of Rishabh Pant, Shreyas Iyer and Ravichandran Ashwin still to come, India will feel that if they capitalise on the bad deliveries then 100 runs can be wiped out in no time. Will they be able to do it though on a pitch that now has more than a few demons in it? We shall find out soon as the first session is coming up soon.

We had pretty exciting cricket on Days 1 and 2 of the game but the best action was reserved for Day 3 as both teams kept on fighting tooth and nail, leaving the game hanging on a knife edge. Bangladesh do have a slight advantage as they have sent the Indian top 4 packing and will know that a couple of early wickets here and the game can be won.

Hello and welcome ladies and gentlemen to Day 4 of the 2nd and final Test match between Bangladesh and India at the Sher-e-Bangla Stadium in Mirpur. What a fascinating contest we have on our hands as the hosts need 6 wickets to win and the visitors need 100 runs. Which team will reign supreme here?
... DAY 4, SESSION 1 ...

Right then, we have had 3 exciting days of Test cricket and after those three days, we can't pick a winner. It looked to be India's game all the way but the hosts have come roaring back and have a real chance of leveling the series here. 100 runs are needed for India to win with 6 wickets in hand and a couple of in-form batters yet to come. Bangladesh will pray that their spin trio comes good and does the job for them. Whatever the result may be, we will surely get a lot of entertainment. Day 4 will begin on Sunday at 9 am IST (3.30 am GMT) but you can join us for the early build-up as usual. Cheers!

The man of the moment, Mehidy Hasan is in for a quick chat. He says that he is happy with his spell. Adds that the wicket is turning well and it is all about hitting the right lengths. Says that they will try to get early wickets tomorrow and Virat Kohli's wicket was an important one. Ends by saying that they need to improve their bowling and do well.

India had the game in the palm of their hands until the second session on Day 3 began but since then, they seemed to have let go of their advantage. They did manage to clean up Bangladesh but did concede at least 50 runs more than they should have as they had the hosts on the ropes at one point. This could prove to be costly as their top order has failed miserably yet again. The skipper, KL Rahul was the first to go and then both Cheteshwar Pujara and Shubman Gill tried to use their feet to counter the spin but were stumped. Virat Kohli occupied the crease without showing much intent and was ultimately dismissed. The only positive with the bat has been Axar Patel who has mustered up important runs for his side. The good thing for India is that the in-form batter, Rishabh Pant and Shreyas Iyer are yet to come but it will be an uphill task when they come out to bat on Day 4.

Bangladesh got bundled out after a few spirited performances with the bat for 231 runs and had 144 runs to play with. They needed wickets in the final session to have a shot at glory and boy, they have dominated with the ball here. Right from the very first ball that Shakib Al Hasan bowled, Bangladesh knew they will get opportunities. Shakib did get a wicket early in the innings and that set the tone. Shakib and Taijul Islam continued to create chances but it was Mehidy Hasan who proved to be the difference-maker as he picked up three wickets for just 12 runs, sending back 3 big guns for India in the process. The hosts have all the momentum going into the fourth day and will look to make early inroads in order to put the opposition under even more pressure.

Wow, what a day of Test cricket have just witnessed! Well, they don't call Day 3 the moving day for nothing. A total of 14 wickets fell throughout the course of the day and in the end, the pendulum did swing in favour of the hosts who will now believe that they can pull off the upset. India still need 100 more runs to win but have lost their top four batters which might play a huge role in the outcome.
FOUR! Slightly shorter and on off, Axar Patel rocks back and punches it past extra covers for a boundary! That will be STUMPS on Day 3.
Goes fuller again, and on off. Axar Patel knocks it to mid off again.
Fuller and on off, Axar Patel defends it to the man at mid off.
Bowls it outside off again, Axar Patel reads it well and lets it go.
Another one outside off, Axar Patel defends it with his pads as the ball lobs towards slips. Dot.
Turning it in from outside off, Axar Patel defends it back towards the bowler.
This one lands on off as well, Axar Patel punches it to extra covers for a single. He keeps his strike for the next over.
Fuller and on off, Axar Patel taps it to short covers.
Bowls it on off, Axar Patel lunges and blocks it solidly.
Tossed up again and outside off, Jaydev Unadkat strokes it away through covers for a single.
Floated up around off, Jaydev Unadkat pushes it towards cover-point.
Fuller and around off, Jaydev Unadkat blocks it out.
Slows it up now and pulls the length back as well. Axar Patel looks to block off the back foot but gets an inside edge onto the pads.
Tossed up, full and outside off, turning in. Axar Patel keeps it out.
This is around off, Jaydev Unadkat pushes it through the cover region for a single.
Another fuller one as this is again defended towards the bowler.
This one lands on leg, Jaydev Unadkat defends it back towards the bowler.
Quicker and on off, Jaydev Unadkat defends it solidly.
Fuller and on off, Jaydev Unadkat taps it to covers for one.
Jaydev Unadkat has been sent in as the nightwatchman.

OUT! TAKEN! An excellent catch by Mominul Haque and Virat Kohli departs for just a run! Full and outside the off stump forcing Kohli to lean forward to play this. He looks to defend it but gets an inside edge off the pads towards short leg and Mominul Haque takes a sharp catch diving to his left. India are in a lot of trouble now as they lose four wickets in quick succession and they still 108 runs to win.
Commentary.Howout: c Mominul Haque b Mehidy Hasan

Bowls it on middle and leg, Axar Patel eases it to the man at mid-wicket for one.
Fuller and outside off, Axar Patel looks to block it but misses.
FOUR! Errs in line and gets punished. Slightly shorter and on off, Axar Patel drills it through mid-wicket for a boundary!
Fuller and outside off, Virat Kohli lunges and blocks it away.
Fuller and on middle, Virat Kohli blocks it and gets an inside edge towards square leg. Dot.
This one lands on off as well, Virat Kohli reads it well and blocks it out.
Bowls it on off, Virat Kohli defends it to mid on.
Another fuller one, Virat Kohli taps it to the man at point.
Fuller and on off, Virat Kohli eases it to the man at short covers.
Bowls it outside off, Axar Patel blocks it to mid off. A maiden from Mehidy Hasan!
Fuller on the stumps, Axar pushes it to the short cover fielder.
Bowls it on middle turning it in, Axar Patel eases it back towards the bowler.
Fuller on the stumps, Axar defends it to the short cover region.
Another fuller one as this is defended towards the man at mid off.
Bowls it fuller and on off, Axar Patel lunges and blocks it away.

Virat Kohli knew it hit the blade and lives to fight another day. This is flighted on a length and drifted in from around off stump. Kohli presses forward to defend but seems to have missed it as the ball raps him on the pads. Taijul Islam appeals loudly and after a long thought, the umpire raises the finger. It is reviewed instantaneously and UltraEdge shows that there was a faint inside edge on it.
Fuller and on off, Kohli taps it to the man at covers.
Bowls it on off, Kohli defends it solidly off the front foot.
Quicker one here, Kohli defends watchfully.
Fuller one this time, Kohli defends it away. Half an appeal as the pad was in front of the bat but the replays show that the ball did hit the bat.
Fuller and on off, Kohli defends it solidly off the front foot.
Turns it in from outside off, Patel defend it solidly off the front foot.
Shorter and outside off turning it away, Patel leaves it alone.
Fuller and on off, Kohli knocks it to mid on for one.
This one lands on off, Kohli eases it to the man at short covers.
Another fuller and on off, Kohli blocks it to short leg.
Fuller and outside off, Kohli looks to defend it but misses.

Holds it back a touch and pulls the length back as well. The ball is delivered around off stump, it turns in and bounces a bit extra as well. Axar Patel gets taken by surprise but manages to keep it out.
Tossed up on off stump, turning in, Axar Patel defends it down the pitch.
Taijul Islam switches to over the wicket and drifts it onto the pads. Axar Patel tickles it through short fine leg and picks up a couple of runs.
Tossed up around leg stump, Axar Patel plays it with soft hands and towards mid-wicket.
Nagging length on off stump, Axar Patel tentatively blocks it out.
Taijul Islam comes back into the attack and starts off with a fuller one on the pads, Axar Patel flicks it straight to square leg.
Mehidy Hasan pulls back the length and bowls it around off, Virat Kohli goes on the back foot to keep it out. A wicket-maiden then for Mehidy.
This is floated up on middle, Kohli reaches forward to defend.
Tossed up on off stump, Kohli keeps it out.

A tad shorter and turning in from around middle. Virat Kohli goes deep in his crease and flicks it right of the man at mid-wicket who makes a half-stop. Kohli denies the single on the misfield and rightly so.
Virat Kohli walks in.

OUT! STUMPED! Mehidy Hasan completely outfoxes Shubman Gill who walks back after a nervy inning. This is nicely flighted on a length and outside off. Gill looks to step out and get to the pitch of the ball but is beaten in the flight. Also, the ball doesn't turn in rather drifts away beating the outside edge. Nurul Hasan whips off the bails in a flash and Gill is well out of his crease. Mehidy Hasan gets his second wicket and India in a spot of bother here. 116 runs still needed with 7 wickets in hand.
Commentary.Howout: st Nurul Hasan b Mehidy Hasan

Commentary.Commentary: This is floated up outside off, Shubman Gill blocks it off the front foot.
Comes from around the wicket now and serves it on a length around off at 140 clicks. Axar Patel plays it toward point.
Goes a bit fuller and angles it across the off stump, Axar Patel shoulders arms at it.
Short again and around off, this is nicely punched away well in front of the square on the off side for a couple of runs.
Hits the length hard and bowls it around off, Axar Patel hops and keeps it out towards mid off.
Good length, angling across the left-hander and it is left alone for the keeper to correct.
Starts off a bit of a loosener. This is a fraction shorter and outside off, Axar Patel slaps it away wide of the man at the backward point fence and collects a couple of runs.
Taskin Ahmed comes into the attack now.
On off stump, this is driven down to long off for a single.
This is speared into middle and leg, Axar Patel gets hurried but manages to keep it out.
Drops it shorter on off and looks to turn it away, Axar Patel mistimes it off the back foot onto the leg side.
Looks to fire this one into middle and leg, Patel stays solid in defense.
Tossed up full on off stump, Axar Patel defends it off the front foot.
This is shorter and around off, Axar Patel backs away and plays it to short extra cover.
Tosses it up full and around leg stump, Shubman Gill comes down the pitch and pushes it to silly mid on.
Floated, full and at the toes, Axar Patel works it 'round the corner for one.
This is drifted onto middle and leg, Patel presses forward to defend.
This is tossed up on off stump and Axar Patel defends it out.
FOUR! Just a fraction shorter and Axar Patel pounces on it. This is bowled around off, Patel rocks back and punches it through covers for a boundary.
Quicker one, on a nagging length and around middle, Axar Patel goes deep in his crease to defend it out.
Nicely tossed up around middle, Shubman Gill watchfully defends it out.
Flighted delivery, Axar Patel uses his feet and drives it back past the bowler for a run.
Turn and bounce! Comes from around the wicket and bowls it on a length around off, the ball turns away square leaving Axar Patel completely bamboozled.
Fuller now and at the stumps, Shubman Gill knocks it down to long on for a single.
Turning in from around middle and Gill blocks it onto the leg side.
Big turn! Tossed up on a shorter length and around off. Shubman Gill comes down the track to block but gets undone by the turn and hit on the pads.
Flatter delivery on the pads, Axar Patel stays back and defends it on the leg side.
Tossed up around off, Shubman Gill uses his feet well and pushes it down to long off for a single.
This is flighted down leg, Axar Patel gets a fine tickle on it. The ball runs away towards the fine leg fence but Mehidy Hasan chases it down and saves a run for his side.
Drops it a bit short and around off, Shubman Gill steers it off the back foot and through point for a single.

Close again and Shubman Gill looks nevry out there. Shakib Al Hasan angles this one in on a nagging length and into the pads. Gill gets pushed onto the back foot and the ball keeps low as well. The ball hits the pads and seems to be going down leg as there is a stifled appeal from Bangladesh.
Tossed up around middle, Shubman Gill keeps it out.

A huge appeal for lbw and the bowler and keeper seem certain about it. The umpire remains unmoved and Shakib Al Hasan doesn't review it either. This is pushed through quicker and into off stump. Axar Patel strides out to defend but gets a faint inside edge onto the pads.
This one is angling into the pads, Axar Patel looks to block but gets it off the inside edge towards square leg.
Around off again and kept out by Axar Patel.
Almost skids through. Nagging length, around off and sliding in. Axar Patel looks to block off the front foot but gets a faint inside edge onto the pads.
This is fired in on off stump, Axar Patel keeps it out.
Axar Patel walks in.

OUT! STUMPED! Nurul Hasan with a brilliant recovery and all of a sudden, India are two down. Mehidy Hasan comes into the attack and gets a wicket off his very first delivery. Tosses it up on a shorter length and well outside off. Cheteshwar Pujara comes down the track but gets beaten in the flight. Pujara tries to adjust but gets an inside edge off the pads. Nurul Hasan just about manages to collect the ball and dislodges the bails. The third umpire checks it and finds that Pujara failed to get his bat down in time and has to walk back.
Commentary.Howout: st Nurul Hasan b Mehidy Hasan

Nicely tossed and on off turning it away, drawing the batter forward. KL Rahul looks to block it off the front foot but gets beaten and gets an outside edge. Nurul Hasan behind the sticks is quick to react to it and takes a sharp catch to his right. Shakib Al Hasan is delighted as India lose their skipper for another low score. Bangladesh have an early and a much needed breakthrough in the chase!

A loud appeal turned and Shakib Al Hasan straightaway goes for a review. Ball Tracking shows that it was just missing leg and the onfield decision stands NOT OUT and Bangladesh lose a review as well!
